I now have a comprehensive understanding of the entire architecture. Let me now produce the detailed implementation plan.

---

## Implementation Plan: Claude Code `custom-title` Support

### Overview

This plan adds support for Claude Code's `/rename` command, which writes `{"type":"custom-title","customTitle":"...","sessionId":"..."}` entries to JSONL session files. The feature is split into two phases: Phase 1 (static parse + display at startup) and Phase 2 (real-time update during follow mode).

---

### Phase 1 -- Parse + Display custom-title (static)

#### 1.1 Add `customTitle` to `SessionFile` (src/core/types.ts)

Add an optional `customTitle?: string` field to the `SessionFile` interface (line 45-49). This is the only type change needed for Phase 1 -- it avoids touching `WatcherSession` until Phase 2.

```typescript
export interface SessionFile {
  path: string;
  mtime: Date;
  agentType: AgentType;
  customTitle?: string;  // <-- new
}
```

#### 1.2 Create `readCustomTitle` utility (new file: src/claude/custom-title.ts)

A single utility function that reads a Claude JSONL file and extracts the last `custom-title` entry. This follows the existing pattern of `readLastAssistantMessage` in `src/claude/watch-builder.ts` (reads file, scans lines from the end).

**Design rationale -- read from the end:**
- `custom-title` can appear multiple times, last one wins
- Files can be large (thousands of JSONL lines)
- Optimization: read entire file but scan from bottom, return on first match. This is the same approach used by `readLastAssistantMessage`. A full streaming reverse-read approach would be over-engineering for Phase 1 (files are typically a few MB at most)

```typescript
// src/claude/custom-title.ts

/**
 * Read the last custom-title from a Claude JSONL session file.
 * Returns the customTitle string, or null if none found.
 * Scans from end for efficiency (last custom-title wins).
 */
export async function readCustomTitle(filePath: string): Promise<string | null> {
  // Read file, split lines, scan from end for type === 'custom-title'
  // Return data.customTitle or null
}
```

**Why a separate file vs. putting it in claude-agent.ts or watch-builder.ts:**
- `claude-agent.ts` is focused on `SessionFinder` and `LineParser` classes
- `watch-builder.ts` is focused on runtime watch orchestration
- A dedicated `custom-title.ts` keeps the concern isolated and testable
- It will be needed in multiple call sites (SessionFinder, index.ts startup, and eventually the onLine handler in Phase 2)

#### 1.3 Populate `customTitle` in `ClaudeSessionFinder` (src/agents/claude/claude-agent.ts)

Modify three methods in `ClaudeSessionFinder` to call `readCustomTitle` after finding the session file:

1. **`findLatest()`** (line 34-77): After determining the latest file, call `readCustomTitle(latest.path)` and set `customTitle` on the returned `SessionFile`.

2. **`findMainBySessionId()`** (line 220-284): Same treatment after finding the best match.

3. **`findBySessionId()`** (line 137-179): The ClaudeSessionResult path constructs a `SessionFile` for `main` -- populate its `customTitle` as well.

**Note:** `findSubagent()` and `findSubagentBySessionId()` do NOT need this -- subagent sessions won't have custom-title per the design constraint.

**Performance consideration:** `readCustomTitle` adds one file read per finder call. Since `findLatest`/`findBySessionId` are only called once at startup (not in hot loops), this is acceptable. The `findLatestInProject` used by super-follow is called every 500ms but does NOT return from `ClaudeSessionFinder` -- it's a standalone function in `auto-switch.ts` and will be addressed separately.

#### 1.4 Display title in startup messages (src/index.ts)

At three locations where `Found:` and `Modified:` are logged (lines 140, 177, 202), add a conditional line after:

```typescript
if (sessionFile.customTitle) {
  log(options.quiet, chalk.cyan(`Title: ${sessionFile.customTitle}`));
}
```

This is straightforward and only triggers for Claude sessions (Codex/Gemini won't have `customTitle`).

#### 1.5 Display title in auto-switch messages (src/index.ts)

At lines 465, 847, 1088, 1332 where switch messages are shown, enhance the message to include title when available. For the Claude non-interactive switch (line 465):

```typescript
// Before: `--- Switched to session ${newSessionId} ---`
// After:
const titleSuffix = customTitle ? ` "${customTitle}"` : '';
chalk.gray(`--- Switched to session ${newSessionId}${titleSuffix} ---`)
```

For the interactive switch (line 847), same pattern. For `findLatestMainSessionInProject` used by super-follow, we'd need to read the custom-title of the new session during the switch. This is already done once in `switchToSession` -- we can call `readCustomTitle(nextSessionFile.path)` there.

#### 1.6 Display title in interactive mode status line (src/interactive/display-controller.ts)

In `buildStatusLine` (line 151-232), the display label for main session is currently:

```typescript
const displayLabel = session.id === 'main' ? 'MAIN' : label;
```

To show the title, we need to pass it into the status line. The cleanest approach: add an optional `displayName?: string` field to `WatcherSession` (src/core/session-manager.ts). When set, the status line uses it instead of 'MAIN'.

**WatcherSession change:**
```typescript
export interface WatcherSession {
  id: string;
  label: string;
  path: string;
  buffer: string[];
  isDone: boolean;
  createdAt: number;
  displayName?: string;  // <-- new: shown in status line when set
}
```

**SessionManager.addSession change:**
```typescript
addSession(id: string, label: string, path: string, displayName?: string): WatcherSession {
  // ... existing code ...
  const session: WatcherSession = {
    id, label, path, buffer: [], isDone: false, createdAt: Date.now(),
    displayName,
  };
  // ...
}
```

**DisplayController.buildStatusLine change (line 185):**
```typescript
const displayLabel = session.id === 'main'
  ? (session.displayName || 'MAIN')
  : label;
```

**Also in showSwitchMessage (line 264):**
```typescript
const switchLabel = session.displayName
  ? `${session.label} "${session.displayName}"`
  : session.label;
chalk.gray(`\n--- Switched to ${switchLabel}`) + ...
```

#### 1.7 Wire up customTitle in interactive mode initialization

In `startClaudeInteractiveWatch` (line 696), after adding the main session:

```typescript
sessionManager.addSession('main', MAIN_LABEL, targetSessionFile.path);
```

Change to:

```typescript
const customTitle = await readCustomTitle(targetSessionFile.path);
sessionManager.addSession('main', MAIN_LABEL, targetSessionFile.path, customTitle ?? undefined);
```

Similarly in `startClaudeMultiWatch`, when a switch happens (line 462-466), read the title for the new session.

---

### Phase 2 -- Real-time update

#### 2.1 Parse `custom-title` in ClaudeLineParser (src/agents/claude/claude-agent.ts)

In the `format()` method's switch statement (line 567-583), add a case:

```typescript
case 'custom-title': {
  const customTitle = (data as { customTitle?: string }).customTitle;
  if (customTitle) {
    return `Session renamed: "${customTitle}"`;
  }
  return '';
}
```

This makes the parser emit a `ParsedLine` with `type: 'custom-title'` and a formatted message. The PrettyFormatter will display it with a generic type label (the `default` case in `formatType` gives `CUST`).

#### 2.2 Add `isCustomTitle` and `customTitleValue` to ParsedLine (src/core/types.ts)

Extend `ParsedLine` with two optional fields:

```typescript
export interface ParsedLine {
  // ... existing fields ...
  /** custom-title event detected (Claude only) */
  isCustomTitle?: boolean;
  /** The new custom title value */
  customTitleValue?: string;
}
```

Update `ClaudeLineParser.format()` to return these fields when parsing `custom-title`:

```typescript
case 'custom-title': {
  const customTitle = (data as { customTitle?: string }).customTitle;
  if (!customTitle) return '';
  // Return formatted string (the parse() caller will build the ParsedLine)
  return `Session renamed: "${customTitle}"`;
}
```

But wait -- `format()` only returns a string. The `parse()` method at line 417 builds the `ParsedLine`. We need to set `isCustomTitle` and `customTitleValue` there. The cleanest approach: handle `custom-title` as a special case in `parse()`, similar to how `assistant` and `toolUseResult` are handled:

```typescript
// In parse(), before the generic format() call:
if (type === 'custom-title') {
  const customTitle = data.customTitle as string;
  if (!customTitle) return null;
  return {
    type: 'custom-title',
    timestamp,
    raw: data,
    formatted: `Session renamed: "${customTitle}"`,
    isCustomTitle: true,
    customTitleValue: customTitle,
  };
}
```

This is cleaner than trying to smuggle the data through `format()`.

#### 2.3 Add `updateSessionDisplayName` to SessionManager (src/core/session-manager.ts)

```typescript
/**
 * Update a session's displayName (e.g., when custom-title changes)
 */
updateSessionDisplayName(id: string, displayName: string): void {
  const session = this.sessions.find((s) => s.id === id);
  if (session) {
    session.displayName = displayName;
  }
}
```

#### 2.4 Add `onTitleUpdate` callback to `OnLineHandlerConfig` (src/claude/watch-builder.ts)

Extend the config interface:

```typescript
export interface OnLineHandlerConfig {
  // ... existing fields ...
  /** Callback when a custom-title event is detected on MAIN session */
  onTitleUpdate?: (title: string) => void;
}
```

In `createOnLineHandler`, after the line `config.onOutput(config.formatter.format(parsed), label);`, add:

```typescript
// Real-time custom-title update
if (label === MAIN_LABEL && parsed.isCustomTitle && parsed.customTitleValue) {
  config.onTitleUpdate?.(parsed.customTitleValue);
}
```

#### 2.5 Wire up real-time title update in `startClaudeMultiWatch` (src/index.ts)

When creating the `onLine` handler, pass `onTitleUpdate`:

```typescript
createOnLineHandler({
  parsers,
  formatter,
  detector,
  onOutput: (formatted) => console.log(formatted),
  verbose: options.verbose,
  shouldOutput,
  onTitleUpdate: (title) => {
    // In non-interactive mode, just log
    log(options.quiet, chalk.cyan(`Session title: "${title}"`));
  },
})
```

#### 2.6 Wire up real-time title update in `startClaudeInteractiveWatch` (src/index.ts)

For interactive mode, the callback also updates the status line:

```typescript
createOnLineHandler({
  parsers,
  formatter,
  detector: activeDetector,
  onOutput: (formatted, label) => sessionManager.handleOutput(label, formatted),
  verbose: options.verbose,
  onTitleUpdate: (title) => {
    sessionManager.updateSessionDisplayName('main', title);
    displayController.updateStatusLine(
      sessionManager.getAllSessions(),
      sessionManager.getActiveIndex()
    );
  },
})
```

#### 2.7 Add `custom-title` type label in PrettyFormatter (src/formatters/pretty-formatter.ts)

In `formatType()`, add:

```typescript
case 'custom-title':
  return chalk.cyan.bold('TITL');
```

---

### Edge Cases

1. **No custom-title in file** -- `readCustomTitle` returns null, `customTitle` stays undefined. All display paths handle this with `?.` / `|| 'MAIN'` fallback.

2. **Multiple custom-title entries** -- `readCustomTitle` scans from end, returns first match (which is the last written). Phase 2 real-time updates always use the latest event.

3. **custom-title in subagent sessions** -- Per design constraint, this won't happen. Even if it did, Phase 2 only triggers `onTitleUpdate` for `MAIN_LABEL`, so subagent titles are safely ignored.

4. **Empty customTitle string** -- The parser returns null (filtered by `if (!customTitle)`), so an empty rename is treated as no title.

5. **Auto-switch to new session** -- When super-follow switches sessions, the `switchToSession` callback rebuilds everything. `readCustomTitle` is called for the new session file to populate `displayName`. If the user hasn't renamed the new session yet, it falls back to 'MAIN'.

6. **Session switch during interactive mode** -- `buildInteractiveState` calls `readCustomTitle` and passes it to `addSession`. The status line immediately reflects the title.

7. **Race with file write** -- Claude Code writes `custom-title` atomically as a JSON line. Since `readCustomTitle` reads the complete file, there's no partial-read risk.

8. **Codex/Gemini agents** -- These code paths never touch `readCustomTitle` or the `onTitleUpdate` callback. The `customTitle` field on `SessionFile` is simply undefined for non-Claude agents.

---

### Testing Approach

1. **Unit test: `readCustomTitle`** (new file: `tests/claude/custom-title.test.ts`)
   - File with no custom-title entries returns null
   - File with one custom-title returns the title
   - File with multiple custom-title entries returns the last one
   - Empty file returns null
   - File with invalid JSON lines (gracefully ignored)
   - custom-title with empty string returns null

2. **Unit test: ClaudeLineParser custom-title** (extend `tests/agents/claude-agent.test.ts`)
   - `parse()` of a `custom-title` line returns `ParsedLine` with `type: 'custom-title'`, `isCustomTitle: true`, `customTitleValue` set
   - Empty customTitle returns null
   - Verify no infinite loop (use existing `collectAllParsedLines` pattern)

3. **Unit test: SessionManager.updateSessionDisplayName** (extend `tests/core/session-manager.test.ts`)
   - Updating displayName on existing session works
   - Updating displayName on non-existent session is a no-op

4. **Unit test: DisplayController.buildStatusLine with displayName** (this is private, test indirectly via `updateStatusLine` or extract to testable helper)
   - Main session with displayName shows title instead of 'MAIN'
   - Main session without displayName shows 'MAIN'

5. **Integration test: createOnLineHandler with onTitleUpdate** (extend `tests/claude/watch-builder.test.ts`)
   - custom-title line on MAIN label triggers `onTitleUpdate` callback
   - custom-title line on subagent label does NOT trigger `onTitleUpdate`

---

### Implementation Sequence

**Phase 1 (4 steps, can be done in one PR):**
1. Add `customTitle` to `SessionFile` in `types.ts`
2. Create `readCustomTitle` in `src/claude/custom-title.ts` + tests
3. Populate `customTitle` in `ClaudeSessionFinder` methods
4. Display in startup messages (`index.ts` lines 140, 177, 202)

**Phase 2 (6 steps, separate PR):**
